'''Julien Amegandjin''' (born May 2, 1940 in [[Togoville]]) is a Togolese academic. He received his education in Togo and France, studying mathematics and statistics at the [[University of Paris]]. He was first a teacher in France, and in the 1970s he was the director of the United Nations's Institut de Formation et de Recherche Demographiques (Institute for Demographic Training and Research) in [[Yaounde]], Cameroon.<ref name="TrzynaSmith1976">{{cite book|last1=Trzyna|first1=Thaddeus C.|last2=Smith|first2=Joan Dickson|title=Population: an international directory of organizations and information resources|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=T-_rAAAAMAAJ|date=1 June 1976|publisher=Public Affairs Clearinghouse|isbn=978-0-912102-22-1|page=3}}</ref> In 1986 he spent  a year devoted to the preparation of his book, ''Démographie mathématique'', which has since become an important textbook for students of demography.<ref name="WunschCaselli2005">{{cite book|last1=Wunsch|first1=Guillaume J.|last2=Caselli|first2=Graziella|last3=Vallin|first3=Jacques|title=Demography: Analysis And Synthesis; A Treatise in Population Studies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nmgNXoiAiU4C&pg=PA788|date=20 December 2005|publisher=Academic Press|isbn=978-0-12-765660-1|page=788}}</ref> He has since devoted himself mainly in West Africa, to the development of agricultural statistics.

